This code block handles the `FLIP` opcode, which corresponds to the `~` operator.
If `a` is an integer (`var_isint(a)`), it performs `var_setint(dst, -a->v.i)`. This is a negation, not a bitwise NOT. This is the root cause of the bug. It should be `~a->v.i`.

In `be_code.c`, at line 609, we see `case ETINT: e->v.i = ~e->v.i; break;`. This is the correct bitwise NOT operation for integer literals during compilation. However, the VM execution path for integer variables is incorrect.

ROOT CAUSE: In `/work/src/be_vm.c` at line 748, the `FLIP` opcode (which corresponds to the bitwise NOT operator `~`) is incorrectly implemented for integer values. Instead of performing a bitwise NOT operation (`~a->v.i`), it performs a negation (`-a->v.i`). This leads to incorrect results when the `~` operator is applied to integer variables.

